    <title>Port workers on the East and Gulf coasts agree to end their strikes</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="Dockworkers Strike Shuts Down Ports On Gulf And East Coasts" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/bMIz8dpAKI96C5jgaubLneBdkN0=/0x1:5816x3878/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73630637/2176461982.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Photo by Anna Moneymaker/Getty Images&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="F2ZuqK"&gt;Many ports along the East and Gulf coasts were shut down, threatening the country’s supply chains, after unionized port workers went on strike &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/10/1/24259395/port-workers-ila-east-gulf-coast-strike-automation"&gt;on Tuesday&lt;/a&gt;. But those workers will return to work after reaching a tentative agreement on wages with the group representing port employers. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="GYYlE7"&gt;As part of the agreement on wages, the United States Maritime Alliance has offered to up wages by 62 percent over a six-year contract, &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/10/03/business/economy/port-strike-suspended.html"&gt;&lt;em&gt;The New York Times&lt;/em&gt; reports&lt;/a&gt;. The two groups still have other issues to negotiate, and they have agreed to extend the “Master Contract” until January 15th, 2025.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="3QTruJ"&gt;The International Longshoremen’s Association, which represents the workers, and the United States Maritime Alliance, which represents their employers, shared a &lt;a href="https://ilaunion.org/joint-statement-regarding-master-contract/"&gt;joint...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
    &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/10/3/24261653/port-workers-strike-tentative-agreement-wages"&gt;Continue reading&amp;hellip;&lt;/a&gt;
  &lt;/p&gt;

</content>
